      <div class="prose-dark">
        <h2 id="fundamental-difference" class="anchor-top">The Fundamental Difference</h2>
        <p>
          Traditional SEO operates on a simple premise: produce content that search engines rank highly, and users will find it in a list of ten blue links. The user sees your result, decides whether to click, lands on your page, and engages. Every step in that journey is visible, trackable, and optimisable.
        </p>
        <p>
          Generative engine optimisation addresses a fundamentally different outcome. When a user asks ChatGPT "what are the best project management tools for agencies" or asks Perplexity "which SEO agencies specialise in AI search", they do not receive a list of links. They receive a synthesised, AI-authored answer that draws on sources the model has already evaluated. Your brand is either in that answer — cited, described, and positioned — or it is absent. There is no page two. There is no position eleven. The answer is the output.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is the core divergence. SEO is about ranking pages so users can choose to click. GEO is about being chosen by an AI model to populate an answer before the user has a choice at all. The mechanics that determine each outcome are related but distinct.
        </p>
        <p>
          Traditional search engines rank pages using signals that have been refined over two decades: the quality and relevance of backlinks, the technical crawlability of the site, the precision of keyword targeting, the authority of the domain, and increasingly the quality of the user experience. These signals are imperfect proxies for the question every search engine is trying to answer: which page best satisfies this query?
        </p>
        <p>
          Large language models approach the same question differently. When a generative engine constructs an answer, it draws on training data and, in retrieval-augmented systems, real-time web content. The model selects sources based on entity authority (does the model know who you are?), content extractability (can the model cleanly quote a factual claim from your page?), and source corroboration (do multiple trusted references describe you consistently?). None of these is a direct equivalent of a backlink or a keyword match.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="what-stays" class="anchor-top">What Stays the Same</h2>
        <p>
          The differences between GEO and SEO are real and significant, but so is the shared foundation. Brands that strip away their SEO investment in favour of GEO-only strategies will underperform in both channels. The fundamentals transfer.
        </p>
        <h3>Content quality is non-negotiable in both</h3>
        <p>
          Search engines demote thin, low-quality, or inaccurate content. So do LLMs. A generative engine will not cite a page that contradicts well-established facts, makes unsubstantiated claims, or offers no genuine informational value. The bar for content quality has not fallen in the transition from SEO to GEO — it has risen. The difference is that LLMs can assess content quality at a semantic level that keyword-based ranking algorithms never could.
        </p>
        <p>
          Content that genuinely answers questions, cites specific data, and provides clear, accurate information serves both disciplines equally well. The structural presentation must change, but the underlying quality requirement is identical.
        </p>
        <h3>Technical site health remains essential</h3>
        <p>
          Crawlability, page speed, mobile responsiveness, and clean site architecture matter in GEO for the same reason they matter in SEO: models cannot cite content they cannot access. A site that blocks AI crawlers entirely (via robots.txt or server configuration) removes itself from retrieval-augmented generation pipelines entirely. A site with broken links, slow load times, and inaccessible content gives AI systems a degraded picture of the brand.
        </p>
        <p>
          Technical SEO hygiene — canonical URLs, structured navigation, clean internal linking — also improves the coherence of entity signals that LLMs rely on. A technically sound site is easier for any machine to understand, whether that machine is a traditional crawler or a language model performing retrieval.
        </p>
        <h3>Domain authority and trust signals persist</h3>
        <p>
          AI models have absorbed years of web data, and that data skews heavily towards established, trusted sources. A domain with strong backlink profiles, editorial citations, and a history of authoritative content starts GEO from a position of advantage. The trust signals that underpin high SEO authority do not disappear in the transition to GEO — they become foundational inputs.
        </p>
        <p>
          A brand with no organic presence, no inbound links, and no third-party mentions is not an entity in any model's understanding of the world. Building that authority through traditional SEO creates the raw material that GEO strategies work with.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="what-changes" class="anchor-top">What Changes</h2>
        <p>
          The differences between GEO and SEO are not superficial. They affect which signals matter most, how competitive advantage is structured, and what you measure to know whether the strategy is working.
        </p>
        <h3>Signals shift from links to entities</h3>
        <p>
          Backlinks are the currency of traditional SEO because they represent one site's endorsement of another. A high volume of high-quality backlinks signals that a page is authoritative on its subject. LLMs process this signal, but they also weight something that SEO has historically underemphasised: entity coherence.
        </p>
        <p>
          An entity is a distinct, knowable object in the world — a person, organisation, product, concept. LLMs construct their understanding of the world through entities and the relationships between them. If your brand exists as a well-defined entity in Wikipedia, Wikidata, Google's Knowledge Graph, and authoritative industry databases, you are structurally visible to AI models in a way that a high-backlink-count, low-entity-presence site is not.
        </p>
        <p>
          GEO requires deliberate entity building: ensuring consistent naming across all platforms, establishing verified attributes, and creating the third-party corroboration that signals notability to knowledge systems.
        </p>
        <h3>Content structure changes from keyword targeting to claim architecture</h3>
        <p>
          Traditional SEO content is structured around keyword intent: identify the query, build content that satisfies it, target the primary keyword in the title, H1, and copy. This model produces content that ranks well in traditional SERPs but is not always optimal for LLM extraction.
        </p>
        <p>
          GEO-optimised content is structured around extractable claims. Each paragraph should function as a self-contained, citable unit. Definitional statements ("GEO is the practice of optimising brand visibility in AI-generated answers") give LLMs clear, quotable text. Specific data points, named examples, and precise attributions give models the kind of grounded information they prefer to cite over vague equivalents.
        </p>
        <p>
          Structured data becomes more important in GEO than it typically is in pure SEO. Schema markup — FAQPage, HowTo, Service, Person, sameAs — provides machine-readable context that helps models understand the content and attribute it correctly to the right entity.
        </p>
        <h3>Measurement replaces rank tracking with citation monitoring</h3>
        <p>
          You cannot track your position in a GEO environment the way you track keyword rankings in SEO. There are no fixed positions. The same query may produce different AI answers for different users, on different platforms, at different times. The measurement framework has to change accordingly.
        </p>
        <p>
          GEO measurement focuses on citation frequency (how often your brand appears in AI answers for a set of target queries), brand accuracy (whether those mentions describe you correctly), sentiment (whether the description is favourable or neutral), and cross-platform reach (consistency of presence across ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, Copilot, and AI Overviews). These metrics require different tooling and different analytical approaches from traditional rank tracking.
        </p>
        <h3>Competitive dynamics compress dramatically</h3>
        <p>
          Traditional SEO allocates ten organic positions on the first page. A competitive market might have fifty well-optimised pages vying for those slots, but ten brands share first-page visibility. The competitive landscape is tight but not zero-sum.
        </p>
        <p>
          Generative AI answers typically cite one to three sources. In practice, the brand that earns the citation in a given AI answer gains disproportionate visibility — not a position in a list, but a direct endorsement in a synthesised response. This compression makes the stakes higher and the value of being the cited source significantly greater. It also means that early investment in GEO creates structural advantages that become progressively harder for late movers to overcome.
        </p>
      </div>

